The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, February 23, 2004 				 L amp;T sets sights abroad for risk-reducing acquisitions
				 	 Naik: On the prowl																								New Delhi, Feb. 22 (PTI): Larsen amp; Toubro (L amp;T) is looking at overseas acquisitions to diversify its domestic business risks.																								We are looking at overseas acquisitions for diversifying our risk portfolio, L amp;T chairman A. M. Naik said here after receiving All India Management Associations (AIMA) J. R. D. Tata corporate leadership award for 2003.																								The move to go global aggressively is a part of companys strategy to safeguard itself against domestic fluctuations, he said, adding that L amp;T is open to inorganic growth proposition.																								L amp;T has put tremendous efforts to develop international business, he said. The sustained focus led to an 80 per cent rise in export order to Rs 2,500 crore from Rs 500 crore over last four years, he added. 																								L amp;T now exports advanced engineering equipment to the US, the UK, Canada, Southeast Asia and China. All the business segments of L amp;T export more than 60 per cent of their manufactured equipment, industrial machinery and products, Naik added.																								On project exports, he said the company executed projects up to a value of Rs 1,500 crore in the domestic market, while in international markets, it currently executes projects valued up to Rs 750-800 crore each.																								L amp;T has been able to establish marketing centres in the US, Europe, Far East, West Asia and African countries for its electrical and electronics business. It has decided to brand some of its products for global companies taking advantage of its manufacturing capabilities.																								Referring to developing indigenous engineering capability to reduce dependence on foreign sources, Naik said, The government should accelerate the privatisation programme, announced two years ago, in the defence sector by implementing its policy announcements.																								This would enable the domestic private industry along with the public enterprises to gear up over the next few years and make the country a net exporter of defence equipment, Naik said.
